# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Chat Template Handler to llama.cpp

## Context

The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format (`[INST]/[/INST]`-based) needs its own named handler distinct from the
existing MISTRAL_V1/V3/V3_TEKKEN variants and the Ministral 3 specialized handler in `common/chat.cpp`.
The new handler must be selectable by name (`"mistral-instruct-v3"`) and also auto-detectable from raw
Jinja template content. The key distinguishing trait from Ministral 3 is the **absence** of
`[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` in the template. All changes are **additive only** — no existing handlers or the public
header (`include/llama.h`) are touched.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Role |
|---|---|
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Internal header: defines `llm_chat_template` enum (new value goes here) |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Implementation: registry map, detection function, apply function |
| `include/llama.h` | **Do not touch** — public C API header |
| `common/chat.cpp` | **Do not touch** — Ministral 3 specialized handler lives here |

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — New enum value in `src/llama-chat.h`

**Where:** Line 60, immediately before `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_UNKNOWN` (last entry).

**Insert:**
```cpp
    LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3,
```

This is purely additive — no existing enum values are reordered or changed.

---

### Step 2 — Registry entry in `src/llama-chat.cpp`

**Where:** Inside the `LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATES` static map (lines 28–81), after the existing
`mistral-v7-tekken` entry (line 38) to keep mistral variants grouped.

**Insert:**
```cpp
    { "mistral-instruct-v3", LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3 },
```

This enables explicit selection by name via `llm_chat_template_from_str("mistral-instruct-v3")`.

---

### Step 3 — Auto-detection in `llm_chat_detect_template`

**Where:** `src/llama-chat.cpp` lines 121–136, inside the inner `else` block of the `[INST]`
branch (the block that currently handles llama2 variants). Insert **before** the llama2 checks.

**Current structure (simplified):**
```cpp
} else if (tmpl.find("mistral") == 0 || tmpl_contains("[INST]")) {
    if (tmpl_contains("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]")) {               // → V7
        ...
    } else if (tmpl_contains("' [INST] ' + system_message")
               || tmpl_contains("[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]")) {   // → V1/V3/V3-Tekken
        ...
    } else {
        // ← INSERT HERE, before llama2 checks
        bool support_system_message = tmpl_contains("<<SYS>>");
        ...
    }
}
```

**Code to insert at the top of the `else` block:**
```cpp
            // Mistral Instruct v0.3: [INST]/[/INST] without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
            // Distinguish from Ministral 3 handler by absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
            // (already guaranteed by this else branch) and by the v0.3-specific
            // single-quoted '[INST] ' literal in the Jinja template.
            if (tmpl_contains("'[INST] '")) {
                return LLM_CHAT_TEMPLATE_MISTRAL_INSTRUCT_V3;
            }
```

**Why this heuristic works:**
- The actual Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 Jinja template uses the literal `'[INST] ' + message['content'] + ' [/INST]'`, making `'[INST] '` (single-quoted, space after) a fingerprint.
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` absence is implicit — this `else` block is only reached when `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` is NOT present (already ruled out by the outer `if`), which is exactly the distinguishing trait from the Ministral 3 handler.
